At line 4, the variable `i` is a dictionary, so when you execute `x[1]*i.values`, you are multiplying an integer (`x[1]`) by the built-in method `values` from `dict`. Even if you put the parenthesis, `i.values()` will return a collection of values from your current second-level dictionary. Therefore, you need to use the key `x`, so that `i[x]` will return an integer:

```python
for i in db.values():
    for x in i.keys():
        if x[1] &gt;= 1:
            print(x[1]*i[x])
```

Another way to solve your problem:

```python
for i in db.values():
    for (_, j), value in i.items():
        if j &gt;= 1:
            print(j*value)
```

